Mammograms save fewer lives than you think
You probably think mammograms save a lot more lives than they actually do. Mammograms save, at most, one additional life for every 1,000 people screened,  of the medical literature found. We tend to think they do a lot more: one survey of 50-year-old American women found them to think an additional 80 lives are saved for the same 1,000 screenings. New England Journal of Medicine The board's defense follows a  Get our newsletter in your inbox twice a week. 